By Nduka Chiejina, (Assistant Editor), Abuja  The Revenue Mobilisation Allocation and Fiscal Commission (RMAFC) has said the revenue-generating agencies made a total remittance of N1, 538,021,801,518.37 into the Federation Account in the first quarter (Q1) of this year. Its Chairman Elias Mbam made this known in Abuja while receiving a Revenue Performance report from the Post-Mortem Sub-Committee of the Federation Account Allocation Committee (FAAC). The report stated that the FIRS made the highest remittance of N759, 857,249,035.40), while the Ministry of Mines and Steel Development (MMSD) surpassed its target for the quarter with N2,469,499,323.04 into government coffers. Mbam further said more N496, 390,010, 655.56 was also remitted into the Federation Account as Value Added Tax (VAT) for the first quarter of the year.  This, according to him, surpassed the targeted tax revenue by N36, 803,760.80, representing 108.01 percent for the period under review. On recoveries of outstanding arrears due to the Federation Account, he said the Commission, in collaboration with the Post-Mortem Sub- Committee of FAAC, also receivedÂ  arrears payments totalling N260,137,577,128.01. This is in addition to N845,123,857,566.32 that the Sub-Committee recovered last year. Others whose contribution in the first quarter of teh year brought funds into the Federation Account to N1.5 trillion include the Nigeria National Petroleum Corporation (NNPC) N47,530,659,945.90; Department of Petroleum Resources (DPR) N452,510,132,616.32; and the Nigeria Customs Service (NCS) N275,654,260,597.69. Mbam noted that RMAFC is committed to increasing revenue generation into the Federation Account and equitable distribution of the accrued revenues to the three tiers of government. 